<br>
The bandwidth/hardware requirements have grown considerably.  They had a few choices, they picked one... but no matter which one, you'd all be complaining:<br>
<br>
1). Up everyone's fee to $15/$20 a month, lots of complaints, and people that barely were willing to pay $10 would probably leave.  <br>
<br>
2). Stop development.  We know what would happen here, but dang programmers are expensive.  Odds are these guys are getting &gt; $100k a year, and the team has grown considerably, takes a lot of you just to cover these guys, and then add all the administrative overhead of &quot;herding cats&quot;...<br>
<br>
3). Reduce Customer Service... Nope, they spent a ton of money trying to fix this,  but they probably can't go much beyond what they are doing for $10.<br>
<br>
4). Create a &quot;premium&quot; service that you pay a bit more for than what you get out of it, but it'll help cover the costs of keeping the #1 MMORPG at $10.<br>
<br>
I have to agree with Alan on this one... look at your Cable bill, and you know cable companies, they have no CS to speak of, and they use a much cheaper medium for delivery.<br>
<br>
Listen to all the new MMORPG's coming out... they all mention that it really can't be done for $10 a month.  EQ had Sony as a big partner to ante up a lot of money to support it.<br>
<br>
Also, read what MS said about Windows95... and what reality was... EQ got a lot closer to what they put on the box than Microsoft EVER has.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying they are perfect, but I am saying that I've gotten a lot more than $10 a month worth out of EQ.  Before EQ I averaged $100 a month on computer games, where it would takea bout 2 weeks to beat it and get bored with it.<br>
<br>
$10 a month is nothing, it's less than you pay for Internet badwidth, less than you pay for cable, less than you pay for telephone.<br>
<br>
