Exactly.  <br>
This is why i feel the pity for the people paying it.  Sure, the benefits are great.  But i doubt they can carry them out when they can't even get a firm grasp on the fundamentals of Good Customer Service.<br>
<br>
You can spend 30 minutes in abusive tells from a disatisfied customer which leads to banning/suspending them or dealing with their pissy emails because they're peeved at the lack of CS.... dragging yet another set of labor hours into the picture.  <br>
<br>
 Or you can spend 5 minutes coming up with a good (consistant!!) solution and give your customer decent CS - even if there's a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> slight</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> chance of them being in the wrong.<br>
<br>
<br>
Which do you think is cheaper?<br>
<br>
Verant has taken the &quot;Hard ass&quot; approach to dealing with Customers.  That can get costly.....  and it also makes us less confident in them when it comes to promising better CS for a nice premium.  <br>
<br>
As for GM events, all we've seen them do for the most part is release unkillable mobs on people, disrupt what might have been the first good group in a week &amp; call it an &quot;Event&quot; with no plot/storyline etc.  <br>
<br>
Sure.  I can recall about 4 decent GM events in 3 years.... but two of them were promo's for their Expansion!!!  C'mon now.  There's plenty of DM's and LARP'ers who could write good Events.  Why not snag some events from them for a few bucks or offer a free 6 month subscription for the best idea.  Make it a contest (great, cheap PR!!) <br>
  <br>
<br>
There's smarter ways to improve the level of customer satisfaction without dishing out a lot of cash.  In return, they could just say - &quot;Hey guys, we need to up the price.  We can't afford to keep going at this rate.&quot;<br>
<br>
In return, they're more than likely to get a - &quot;hey man, love the game.  I'd be happy to pay the extra $5 - $7.&quot;<br>
<br>
We've paid $10 for 3 years...  that's <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Cheap</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  If they had a happier, more loyal player base, asking a smidge more per customer, without feeling guilty, would not be an issue. <br>
<br>
